<subSubSection id="2DF0ACA1FFFBFFC4FF71FF69FE69FE27" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="description">
<paragraph id="6555FF2AFFFBFFC4FF71FF69FD72FF7B" blockId="19.[151,1436,150,393]" box="[151,655,186,213]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
(
<figureCitation id="FDD1E3AFFFFBFFC4FF79FF69FF05FF7B" box="[159,248,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="66.[151,250,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox="[210,1376,198,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-32@66.[201,1387,181,1952]" captionTargetPageId="66" captionText="FIGURE 13. Southeast Asian Eudocima and Eudocima sikhimensis group adults (dorsal aspect)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6605531" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6605531/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figs 13</figureCitation>
: A–B, 20: H, 26: A–B, 31: P, 95: M)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6555FF2AFFFBFFC4FF71FF0DFE69FE27" blockId="19.[151,1436,150,393]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
This species could be mistaken for sympatric 
<taxonomicName id="A2EA84A9FFFBFFC4FD71FF0DFCEBFF56" baseAuthorityName="Banziger &amp; Honey" baseAuthorityYear="1984" box="[663,790,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Eudocima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurantia">
<emphasis id="579E2338FFFBFFC4FD71FF0DFCEBFF56" box="[663,790,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">E. aurantia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be separated by the much broader marginal band reaching the outer margin of the hindwing, the larger medial patch, and the smaller size (
<quantity id="A21252CFFFFBFFC4FB8AFED1FB15FEB3" box="[1132,1256,259,285]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.9" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="3.8" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="39.0" valueMax="40.0" valueMin="38.0">38–40 mm</quantity>
, n=2) vs (
<quantity id="A21252CFFFFBFFC4FAB3FED0FF38FEEF" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.1" metricValueMax="5.4" metricValueMin="4.8" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="51.0" valueMax="54.0" valueMin="48.0">48–54 mm</quantity>
, n=7). Relative to allopatric 
<taxonomicName id="A2EA84A9FFFBFFC4FDE5FEF5FD96FEEF" baseAuthorityName="Okano" baseAuthorityYear="1964" box="[515,619,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Eudocima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="okurai">
<emphasis id="579E2338FFFBFFC4FDE5FEF5FD96FEEF" box="[515,619,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">E. okurai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the forewing shape is less elongate, there is no green spot inside the reniform, and the distal side of the medial patch has a less distinct concave indentation. This species is endemic to the island of New 
<collectingCountry id="1DFDBFBAFFFBFFC4FEDDFEBDFE6DFE27" box="[315,400,367,393]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Guinea</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
